In his performance, Lawrence D. "Butch" Morris took
apart his cornet piece by piece. He blew air through.
its valves and tubing, amplifying the sound through a
mic, and ended by playing the horn's mouthpiece. After
showing off his embouchure, he stuck out his tongue."
A cornetist, conductor, and composer, Morris devel-
oped a process he called "Conduction"-an invocation:
of the scientific term for the transfer of heat or energy,
and short for "conducted improvisation." Morris devel-
oped a vocabulary of hand signs and baton gestures to
direct ensemble members; rather than using musical
notation, they composed music with one another, live."
Morris's systemized approach to improvisation fused
interpretation with composition and the instrumentalist
to the ensemble. He used a sign he called "Pedestrian" to
prompt musicians to play at liberty-bringing "something
into the ensemble rather than 'on top of' it"-which dis-
tinguished his approach from jazz's historical prioritiza-
tion of the soloist." Paradoxically, Morris trademarked his
method and the diagrammatic instructions that appear in
his posthumously published workbook.
Morris regularly collaborated with visual artists
he met through JAM, including Senga Nengudi (see
Chronology, p. 91) and David Hammons, as well as with
non-jazz musicians, dancers, and poets. Conduction
continues to offer a practice of communion for people
across disciplines who want to create as they go. -TJL

The Critic's Choice was the first and only set of perfor-
mances realized as part of what was envisioned as an
annual series showcasing artists selected by a group
of critics and producers. Presented at the Village
Gate, a Greenwich Village nightclub, this "music fes-
tival with a twist" featured "new concepts" from per-
formers chosen in response to the question "What's
new among artists of color?" Writers Michael Alan
Gonzales, Greg Tate, and Peter Watrous, among others,
generated lists from which the final roster was developed.
The resulting suite of shows spanned jazz, gospel, accor-
dion, and electronic sounds, creating an ecstatic musical
experience-and serving as yet another example of JAM's
commitment to supporting experimental and emerg-
ing artists who were rarely platformed elsewhere. (The
Shared Resources program, which ran from 1985 to 1986,
offered free space for rehearsals and performances, and
made JAM on Broadway the first venue to present the
work of several artists.)
On the second night of the festival, Graham Haynes
and No Image played work guided by the Brooklyn-based
movement M-Base's philosophy of sound making, which
utilized improvisation to create expressive music derived
from personal experience." They were followed by Steve
Coleman and Five Elements, a group formed by Haynes
and Coleman in 1979 that turned ordinary funk on its head
by breaking from traditional song structure and using
pop and jazz sounds. The band 24-7 Spyz, which had per-
formed earlier the same evening, aimed to be "the first
of [their] kind to cross boundaries of musical thought. To
play for all races, creeds, colors and to be accepted by
all." In this pursuit, the group blended reggae, heavy
metal, soul, funk, and thrash to develop a genre of its
own. Hailing from the Bronx, 24-7 Spyz's four members
were involved in the Black Rock Coalition-founded by
Greg Tate, Konda Mason, and Vernon Reid (who also per-
formed in Critic's Choice)-which sought to encourage
the creative liberation of Black artists whose work didn't
fit the music industry's stereotypes of "Black music" (see
Chronology, p. 155). -YK
